You can do something like to Pawel&#39;s Hangfire suggestion with Functions. It&#39;s similar to what you are already doing. A web job acts a host behind the scenes and it runs the individual functions on the timers set in each function&#39;s [timer trigger][1]. You just won&#39;t have to do the messy work of keeping track of schedules or setting up the webjob. 

You would run one function per job and use [C# script (.csx files)][2] to keep the functions dynamic. The work comes in managing the function scripts.

Here&#39;s how I would convert your project. Feel free to borrow, edit, or make this your own way:

 1. To make it easier to make updates I would take the logic of your calculations and make them into either a class library inside the `bin` folder or convert them to .csx files and add them to a `./shared` folder under your `wwwroot` folder. You&#39;ll then be able to make use of it in the functions without duplicating it by using `#load &quot;..\shared\calculation1Logic.csx&quot;`at the top of the function&#39;s .csx file. This is optional

So now we have: &lt;br/&gt;
- wwwroot &lt;br/&gt;
| - website (if you are using the same app service) &lt;br/&gt;
| - shared &lt;br/&gt; 
| | - calculation1Logic.csx &lt;br/&gt;
| | - calculation2Logic.csx &lt;br/&gt;

*or*

| bin &lt;br/&gt;
| | calculationLogic.dll &lt;br/&gt;

----------

 2. Make some function templates that wrap each one of those calculations.

*calculation1Function.csx* example

    #load &quot;..\shared\calculation1Logic.csx&quot;
    
    using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
    
    public static void Run(TimerInfo myTimer, ILogger log)
    {
        log.LogInformation($&quot;running calculation 1: {DateTime.Now}&quot;);
        calculation1Logic(myTimer, log);
    }


----------


 3. To create a new job, I would use the `createfunction` endpoint [in the Azure Management API][3] and pass it that template and a timer binding with the schedule converted to CRON syntax. Since this is much easier to create from an example, there&#39;s one in [this][4] MSDN thread. It is in Node, but as I am using .csx instead of precompiled code the same method of dynamically adding functions will work. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; Make sure to make the function names unique and store them so that you can edit or delete them later.

Now these are the files I have based on how this will get converted from the API request: &lt;br/&gt;
- wwwroot &lt;br/&gt;
| - website (if you are using the same app service) &lt;br/&gt;
| - shared &lt;br/&gt; 
| | - calculation1Logic.csx &lt;br/&gt;
| | - calculation2Logic.csx &lt;br/&gt;
| - User1_Calculation1 &lt;br/&gt;
  | | - run.csx&lt;br/&gt;
  | | - function.json&lt;br/&gt;
  | | - function.proj&lt;br/&gt;
| - User2_Calculation2&lt;br/&gt;
  | | - run.csx&lt;br/&gt;
  | | - function.json&lt;br/&gt;
  | | - function.proj&lt;br/&gt;
| - host.json (part of the functions runtime along with extensions.csproj)&lt;br/&gt;
| - extensions.csproj&lt;br/&gt;
| - bin&lt;br/&gt;


----------
 4. Editing the schedule. This is where it gets a bit tricky. There are a couple ways to do this. The safest is to delete and re-add the function each time. The other is to replace the `function.json` with one with the updated binding. This way is a bit outside of what you &#39;should&#39; do, but it allows for dynamic rebindings. `function.json` is a simple file if you just have the one binding, so you should be able to generate it progromaticaly.

*function.json* example

    {
      &quot;bindings&quot;: [
        {
          &quot;name&quot;: &quot;myTimer&quot;,
          &quot;type&quot;: &quot;timerTrigger&quot;,
          &quot;direction&quot;: &quot;in&quot;,
          &quot;schedule&quot;: &quot;0 */5 * * * *&quot;
        }
      ]
    }

You can replace files in the App Service without a full deployment by accessing the files by FTP. Now, because changing the file via FTP [doesn&#39;t notify][5] the host process that it has a new schedule to implement, you will need to send a request to `/syncfunctiontriggers` [via the management API][6] to get it to update. This doesn&#39;t restart the full app, but if you are changing schedules often, you may want to have that API call run on a timer-- every minute or whatever interval works best for you.


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-bindings-timer
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-reference-csharp
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/appservice/webapps/createfunction
  [4]: https://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/f4c91356-4de4-481c-83dc-7974f9ab1aae/creating-a-function-dynamically-using-azure-rest-api?forum=AzureFunctions
  [5]: https://github.com/Azure/Azure-Functions/issues/210
  [6]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/appservice/webapps/syncfunctiontriggers

Each `setState` call results in a different state, you may want to use [Destructuring assignment][1] on `responseJson.data` like so: `this.setState({ ...responseJson.data });`

